children.value: Nadasky reveals in his journal that, despite his best attempts to avoid it, the King sent a frigate — the HMS Ajax — to chase after the Santíssima Vitória in an attempt to retrieve the Sceptre of Capon. No good came from this command: La Corona's flagship was never seen again, and the Ajax's crew all lost their lives after being stranded on an island without fresh water for a week. Her Majesty believes that you may find more clues about the whereabouts of the flagship if you look into the fate of Richardson and his sailors.

children.value: La Corona’s fleet is vast in size and number, but ours staffed with seamen both seasoned and loyal. We have a chance of winning a decisive victory against the enemy here at Trelawney — but not if we fixate on recovering the sceptre, as the King is insisting... I admit, taking the talisman would greatly damage La Corona's national spirit, but what of our own?— when a thousand or more sailors are sent to their deaths for a trinket! No, we must have no other thought than employing the best tactics to win the day.

Since the King will not now leave the safety of the fortress atop the cliffs, we may be able to blame the fog for not complying with his signals.
There were other incidents today. At 3pm we intercepted two enemy gunboats, and ran them aground between two small islands to the Southeast, with cliffs like two guard dogs facing one another.
At 4:30pm we discovered a frigate bearing the emblem of La Corona smuggling crates from a pirate cove amid the spiral-shaped cluster of islands that lie due east.
Lastly, we had a skirmish with a ship-of-the-line near an old watchtower between the three large islands due west. She sank with all her cargo.

children.value:
La Corona opened fire this morning. We engaged in battle at 10am, southeast of the region, and it lasted until seven in the evening.
We lost many good men today— the sly young Admiral Silva having deployed mines to protect the enemy convoy. It was the King's command that we attack in a single line, parallel to the enemy formation. Fortunately, I was able to persuade the fleet to ignore this instruction, and instead arrange themselves in two perpendicular columns to cut the enemy line, and as a corollary, avoid the mines. Still our lead ships were blown open, but it left a path clear for the rest of us. The enemy fleet, being snipped into thirds, were vulnerable to broadsides. We proceeded to drive them toward their own mines, and though in the mayhem there were casualties on both sides, we knew victory for the Empire had been won.
We thank those brave sailors who lost their lives today that we ourselves survived, and shall never forget their sacrifice. The price would have been far greater had we sworn blind obedience to the King's strategy.

It will doubtless anger him to hear his orders were defied, but I stand by my decision. It may even please him to hear I have been wounded for my arrogance. It is likely my dress and decorations made me a conspicuous target, and I took musketfire to one side.
My arm still has full function— and my head is not half as foggy as the doctor thinks it might be— so I will continue to command until our operation here is concluded. La Corona may have suffered a defeat of magnitude today, but their flagship— the gargantuan Santíssima Vitória— managed to escape unscathed.

children.value:
The King is indeed mad. He appears to care nothing for our victory, and was upset in the extreme to learn that we hadn't yet begun pursuit of the Santíssima Vitória, for he is adamant that the Sceptre of Capon is aboard.
Having received word that the flagship was heading northeast, His Majesty ordered our Captain Richardson — of the HMS Ajax — to go after her. Under no circumstances will he permit us to accompany them. I have tried to inform the King that the Ajax is ill-equipped for the duel, but my injury leaves me weak, and I have had to retire to my quarters. Santíssima Vitória may be the largest man-of-war ever built. Richardson knows he leads his men to their deaths, but he has always been a man unswerving in his sense of duty.

children.value:
It is unseasonably, morbidly hot. A rowboat was found this morning, beached on the headland— brought on the current presumably, for its occupants are three days dead of thirst. In a clenched hand, a letter from Richardson; these men he sent to find help; the crew of the Ajax surviving a clash with the Santíssima Vitória only by swimming to an island southeast of the headland.
We immediately dispatch a rescue boat, but it is too late: Richardson and his crew have met the same fate. We find no trace of the Santíssima Vitória either. His Majesty's reaction is predictable. These lives are on his hands, yet he weeps only for the sceptre.
My wounds fester, and my fever worsens. The doctor says I must put down my pen.
